English

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

The river is first attested 877 as Terstan. The name is of Brythonic origin, possibly related to Welsh trais (“violence, battle”).

Noun

[edit]

Test (plural Tests)

  1. (cricket) A Test match.

Alternative forms

[edit]
  • test

Derived terms

[edit]
  • timeless Test

Proper noun

[edit]

Test

  1. A river in Hampshire, England, which empties into the Solent near Southampton.

Derived terms

[edit]
  • Test Valley

References

[edit]
  • https://www.hantsfieldclub.org.uk/publications/hampshirestudies/digital/1990s/vol53/Breeze.pdf

Anagrams

[edit]
  • ETTs, Etts, TETS, TETs, Tets, sett, stet, tets

German

[edit]
German Wikipedia has an article on:
Test
Wikipedia de

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /tɛst/, [tɛst]
  • Audio (Germany (Berlin)):(file)
  • Rhymes: -ɛst

Etymology 1

[edit]

Borrowed from English test, from Old French test (“pot; melting pot, especially one in which metals were tried”), from Latin testum (“pot”). Compare etymology 2 below. The development from “melting pot” to “procedure of testing metals” also happened natively in earlier German, but the further generalisation is exclusively English.

Noun

[edit]

Test m (strong, genitive Tests or Testes, plural Tests or (colloquial) Teste, diminutive Testchen n)

  1. test
Usage notes
[edit]
  • The commoner plural is Tests. The form Teste is chiefly colloquial.
Declension
[edit]

indef. def. noun def. noun
nominative ein der Test die Tests, Teste2
genitive eines des Tests, Testes der Tests, Teste2
dative einem dem Test, Teste1 den Tests, Testen2
accusative einen den Test die Tests, Teste2

1Now rare, see notes.
2Colloquial.

Etymology 2

[edit]

From Middle High German test (“melting pot”), from Old French test, from Latin testum.

Noun

[edit]

Test m (strong, genitive Testes, plural Teste)

  1. (obsolete) melting pot
    Synonyms: Tiegel, Schmelztiegel
Declension
[edit]
Declension of Test [masculine, strong]
singular plural
indef. def. noun def. noun
nominative ein der Test die Teste
genitive eines des Testes der Teste
dative einem dem Test, Teste1 den Testen
accusative einen den Test die Teste

1Now rare, see notes.
